 Whether it’s offering a comforting look to a stranger in need, doing charity work, giving a kiss to a sulking partner, or choosing a career as a nurse, doctor, or mental health professional—your role is to heal.</li>\r\n<li>However, be mindful of the empathy that comes with your nurturing nature. This can form the foundation for a career away from illness or suffering. You could become a wonderful teacher who nurtures young minds, or a brilliant actor or writer—because you understand people, you know how to portray them.</li>\r\n<li>People with Expression Number 6 often become great leaders, thanks to their nurturing confidence. You can move people, inspire them to follow your lead. You heal their wounds through the symbols in your writing or the characters you bring to life. Humanity needs more people like you.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Perfectionism</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Your nurturing doesn’t stop at people—it extends to hobbies, charity, and volunteer work. But your perfectionism opens up other career doors. Perfectionism is a skill that can serve you well in any task. But it can also become a weakness.</li>\r\n<li>You must learn to be more flexible, because your high standards can lead to frustration when things don’t go as planned. You may become discouraged, fearful, anxious, or insecure. Perhaps it’s those very fears that push you to be so perfect.</li>\r\n<li>You need to be kinder to yourself and those around you. Not everyone can meet your standards—not even you. You know that nurturing part of yourself? Let it flow—on yourself. Take time to love yourself, too.</li>\r\n<li>Create beauty around you—but allow that beauty to be messy and imperfect. If you release your need for control more often, your goals will evolve naturally and your life will flourish.</li>\r\n<li>You have what it takes to be the best, to build the best team, even the best family. Show the love you wish to see in the world.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Romance and Love</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Your nurturing qualities and your perfectionism can sometimes clash—especially in love.</li>\r\n<li>You are loyal to those you love, to those you hire, and to your family or workplace. You always care and worry for them.</li>\r\n<li>But you need to be careful about where you place that care—not everyone needs or wants to be cared for so intensely.</li>\r\n<li>You must remember that balance is essential in every part of life. So when you reflect on things, know that perfection is not truly attainable. Sometimes, your concerns are just misplaced.</li>\r\n<li>Don’t let your nurturing or perfectionist tendencies overwhelm your romantic life. Not everything needs to be fixed, tended to, or perfected—life, and love, are rarely flawless.</li>\r\n</ul>
